pull_request.body:
Thanks for assigning this issue to me. I'm starting to work on it and will keep this PR's description up to date as I form a plan and make progress.

Original issue description:

> @copilot
> 
> â¸»
> 
> Summary
> 
> The NOEMI Survey App needs a full sync to the updated docs/noemi-survey-config.json, a UI polish pass to meet brand requirements (luxury, elegance, sophistication, mobile-first), a working tutorial flow in the swipe game, and database repairs: several .sql files do not run cleanly, and the runtime schema is out of sync with the appâ€™s expectations. Update tests accordingly.
> 
> â¸»
> 
> Goals
> 	â€¢	Render exactly what the updated JSON specifies (survey + game tutorial).
> 	â€¢	Make the survey UI consistent, refined, and mobile-first.
> 	â€¢	Ensure all migrations run safely on a fresh Supabase DB.
> 	â€¢	Bring live schema into alignment with supabase/expected-schema.sql.
> 	â€¢	Update unit/E2E tests to reflect the new copy and flows.
> 
> â¸»
> 
> Scope of Work (Checklists)
> 
> 1) Survey UI & Copy
> 	â€¢	Sync all copy to docs/noemi-survey-config.json.
> 	â€¢	Replace â€œHow do you identify?â€ â†’ â€œWhat is your gender?â€.
> 	â€¢	Remove â€œritualâ€ language across title, subtitle, prompts, options.
> 	â€¢	Ensure app uses JSON as source-of-truth (no stale strings in code).
> 	â€¢	Tighten spacing & type scale (mobile-first) in src/index.css.
> 	â€¢	Reduce headline sizes (h1, .group-title) using clamp(...).
> 	â€¢	Use tighter vertical rhythm: prefer var(--space-2|3) within question blocks and --space-4 between blocks.
> 	â€¢	Keep lines at ~65â€“75ch width where applicable; maintain max-width caps.
> 	â€¢	Standardize input widths (notably Q1) via reusable classes in src/index.css:
> 	â€¢	.survey-input, .survey-select, .survey-textarea â†’ width: 100%, max-width: 560px, box-sizing: border-box.
> 	â€¢	Apply to all inputs/selects/textareas in src/components/Survey.jsx.
> 	â€¢	Eliminate fragile selectors that cause style bleed:
> 	â€¢	Replace .survey-wrapper .stack:first-child with a named container class (e.g., .progress-summary) and update markup in Survey.jsx.
> 	â€¢	Modularize question rendering in Survey.jsx:
> 	â€¢	Extract SingleSelectQuestion, MultiSelectQuestion, ScaleQuestion, etc., for consistency and easier styling.
> 	â€¢	Welcome screen cleanup in src/components/App.jsx:
> 	â€¢	Ensure survey.meta.title, subtitle, and CTA reflect JSON.
> 	â€¢	Remove mystical â€œritualâ€ phrasing.
> 	â€¢	A11y:
> 	â€¢	Every control has a <label htmlFor>.
> 	â€¢	Focus rings visible and tasteful.
> 	â€¢	Click/tap targets â‰¥ 40px.
> 
> Acceptance (UI):
> 	â€¢	Headings reduced and consistent.
> 	â€¢	No styling bleed from :first-child.
> 	â€¢	Inputs full-width on mobile; capped on larger screens.
> 	â€¢	All copy reflects JSON updates.
> 	â€¢	Axe audit has no new violations.
> 
> â¸»
> 
> 2) Swipe Game & Tutorial
> 	â€¢	Tutorial cards: read tutorial sequence defined at the bottom of docs/noemi-survey-config.json and present it before the game starts.
> 	â€¢	Replace the hard-coded sequence in src/hooks/useSwipeGame.js with JSON-driven content.
> 	â€¢	Support â€œNext / Startâ€ CTAs.
> 	â€¢	Persist tutorial state:
> 	â€¢	Store a â€œtutorial seenâ€ flag in localStorage.
> 	â€¢	Add â€œView tutorialâ€ link within game UI to replay.
> 	â€¢	Game polish:
> 	â€¢	Align button and deck spacing with tightened tokens.
> 	â€¢	Confirm arrow keys map correctly (Right=Like, Left=Dislike, Up=Love, Down=Unsure).
> 	â€¢	Maintain focus management after swipe.
> 	â€¢	Copy cleanup:
> 	â€¢	Remove â€œritualâ€ language from tooltips, headings, helper text.
> 
> Acceptance (Game):
> 	â€¢	JSON tutorial displays on first run, can be replayed, and is skippable.
> 	â€¢	Keyboard and touch swipes work; instant visual feedback remains.
> 	â€¢	Game UI respects new spacing and type scale.
> 
> â¸»
> 
> 3) Database & SQL (Supabase / Postgres)
> 
> Problem: Some .sql files fail; app expects tables/columns/policies that may not exist or differ in production. Must repair with safe, additive migrations.
> 	â€¢	BEST TO DELETE EVERYTHING AND START FROM SCRATCH (DROP ALL TABLES AND BEGIN FRESH WITH NEW SUPABASE DEPLOY INSTRUCTIONS)
> 	â€¢	Save the report as a GitHub Actions artifact and paste a summary in this issue.
> 	â€¢	If no DB URL is supplied, at least validate expected schema syntax (script supports this).
> 	â€¢	Migrations must apply cleanly on a fresh DB:
> 	â€¢	supabase/migrations/0001_init.sql (baseline)
> 	â€¢	supabase/migrations/0002_add_design_tables.sql (design tables, safe column adds, indexes, RLS)
> 	â€¢	supabase/migrations/0003_fix_participants_rls_policies.sql (RLS fixes for participants and swipes)
> 	â€¢	If any fail, add new NNNN_description.sql migrations that only use:
> 	â€¢	CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS
> 	â€¢	ALTER TABLE â€¦ ADD COLUMN with existence checks
> 	â€¢	CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS
> 	â€¢	DROP POLICY IF EXISTS + CREATE POLICY
> 	â€¢	No destructive operations; never drop/alter types on live data without a dedicated migration plan & manual approval.
> 	â€¢	Align to supabase/expected-schema.sql:
> 	â€¢	Ensure participants includes: email, marketing_opt_in, answers jsonb, location_data jsonb, is_complete boolean, progress text, created_at, updated_at.
> 	â€¢	Ensure design_sets, designs, swipes exist with required indexes and RLS.
> 	â€¢	RLS policies:
> 	â€¢	anon can INSERT into participants and swipes and SELECT them for analytics.
> 	â€¢	anon can SELECT design_sets and designs.
> 	â€¢	authenticated has full access for admin operations.
> 	â€¢	Verify with a policy existence check (see 0003 approach); add verification DO $$ blocks if needed.
> 	â€¢	Seeds / static content:
> 	â€¢	Confirm /public/designs/index.json exists and is current.
> 	â€¢	Confirm any generator script (e.g., scripts/split_quadrants.py) outputs the structure the game expects.
> 	â€¢	DB health banner (src/components/DbHealthBanner.jsx):
> 	â€¢	Ensure checkDbHealth validates new tables and surfaces helpful diagnostics.
> 	â€¢	Improve copy and add a â€œcopy diagnosticsâ€ success state.
> 
> Acceptance (DB):
> 	â€¢	Fresh Supabase DB applies all migrations without error.
> 	â€¢	check-schema-drift.sh reports no drift against expected-schema.sql.
> 	â€¢	Anonymous survey submissions and swipes work end-to-end.
> 	â€¢	Policies verified present; CI job captures a drift report artifact.
> 
> â¸»
> 
> 4) Tests
> 	â€¢	Unit / component (Vitest + RTL):
> 	â€¢	Update label queries to match new copy (e.g., Gender question).
> 	â€¢	Ensure each question type has a rendering & interaction test.
> 	â€¢	Add tests that ensure no styling bleed (first option unaffected).
> 	â€¢	E2E (Playwright):
> 	â€¢	Welcome â†’ Survey â†’ Game happy path.
> 	â€¢	Tutorial appears on first play, can be skipped/replayed.
> 	â€¢	Keyboard and swipe inputs recorded to Supabase (mock if needed).
> 	â€¢	Visual expectations for spacing/headings at mobile widths.
> 	â€¢	DB validations (mocked):
> 	â€¢	Test schema drift script wrapper or a small Node wrapper that asserts non-empty diff triggers a failure state in CI.
> 	â€¢	Snapshots / visual:
> 	â€¢	Re-record when UI changes are intentional.
> 	â€¢	Add minimal visual checks for type scale and spacing changes.
> 
> Acceptance (Tests):
> 	â€¢	All tests green locally and in CI.
> 	â€¢	Coverage includes at least one flow per question type and the tutorial path.
> 
> â¸»
> 
> 5) Misc Codebase Hygiene
> 	â€¢	Services & utils: Review supabaseClient.js, analytics.js, geolocation.js for robust error handling and logging.
> 	â€¢	Docs:
> 	â€¢	README.md: update usage, dev modes (?dev=true, ?play=true), tutorial mention.
> 	â€¢	AGENTS.md: reflect modular components and CSS token usage.
> 	â€¢	Add comments to docs/noemi-survey-config.json describing fields and constraints.
> 	â€¢	Env & examples:
> 	â€¢	Add .env.example with VITE_SUPABASE_URL, VITE_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY, and any required flags.
> 	â€¢	Add a quickstart section for local DB testing with Supabase CLI.
> 	â€¢	CI pipeline:
> 	â€¢	Ensure CI runs: pnpm install, pnpm lint, pnpm test, pnpm test:e2e, pnpm build, scripts/check-schema-drift.sh.
> 	â€¢	Upload schema drift report as artifact on failure.
> 	â€¢	Perf & a11y:
> 	â€¢	Image preloading in the game is already implemented; validate that it doesnâ€™t block input.
> 	â€¢	Recheck keyboard nav and screen reader labels across survey and game.
> 
> â¸»
> 
> How to Reproduce (Current Issues)
> 	1.	Copy mismatch: Launch app and observe any text not matching docs/noemi-survey-config.json (gender prompt, ritual wording).
> 	2.	Style bleed: Inspect first items in answer lists; confirm no unintended styles caused by :first-child.
> 	3.	Input widths: Q1 sub-questions should not have inconsistent widths on mobile and desktop.
> 	4.	Tutorial: Game should show JSON-driven tutorial; currently the sequence may be hard-coded in useSwipeGame.js.
> 	5.	DB failures: Apply migrations to a fresh Supabase instance; note any errors or missing policies/tables.
> 
> â¸»
> 
> Proposed Implementation Notes
> 	â€¢	Keep all database changes non-destructive; if breaking changes are required, open a separate PR with a data-safe plan.
> 	â€¢	Encapsulate styles using CSS custom properties and named classes; avoid global selectors that target structural positions.
> 	â€¢	Read tutorial config from JSON, not code, to prevent drift.
> 	â€¢	Put all copy behind JSON to avoid stale strings in JSX.
> 
> â¸»
> 
> Commands
> 
> # Install & run
> pnpm install
> pnpm dev
> 
> # Lint / typecheck / tests
> pnpm lint
> pnpm test
> pnpm test:e2e
> pnpm build
> 
> # Supabase / schema checks (requires SUPABASE_DB_URL or DATABASE_URL)
> ./scripts/check-schema-drift.sh
> 
> # (Dev-only) Reset DB
> # supabase db reset
> 
> 
> â¸»
> 
> Definition of Done
> 	â€¢	No copy mismatches; all text is JSON-driven.
> 	â€¢	UI spacing/type standardized; inputs consistent; no style bleed.
> 	â€¢	Tutorial is JSON-driven, persists â€œseenâ€ state, and is replayable.
> 	â€¢	All migrations apply cleanly; schema drift check passes.
> 	â€¢	Unit/E2E tests updated and passing; CI green.
> 
> â¸»
> 
> If anything blocks progress (e.g., missing Supabase credentials), post diagnostics in this issue and PR and proceed with mocked paths where possible.

type.name: Feature
type.description: A request, idea, or new functionality

issue.body:
### Terms

- [X] I have searched [open and closed feature requests](https://github.com/scribe-org/Scribe-Data/issues?q=is%3Aissue+label%3Afeature)
- [X] I agree to follow Scribe-Data's [Code of Conduct](https://github.com/scribe-org/Scribe-Data/blob/main/.github/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md)

### Description

This issue deals with adding data to [Wikidata](https://www.wikidata.org/) that could indicate which nouns in Spanish switch their articles to avoid difficult pronunciations. An example: agua (water) is feminine, but it's "el agua" to avoid "la agua" (but still "las aguas").

It would be convenient if [Wikidata](https://www.wikidata.org/) would also have a widely used article property such that nouns that have articles that don't match their gender could be indicated when they're annotated. This could be as simple as putting the correct article in the gender annotation.

pull_request.body:
## Feat: Implement Auth & Onboarding Redirect Logic in GoRouter and Refactor Navigation

**Description:**

This pull request introduces sophisticated redirect logic within `GoRouter` to manage user navigation based on their onboarding completion status and authentication state. It also includes several code refactorings, such as removing TODOs, adding `mounted` checks for context safety, and migrating more navigation calls to use `go_router`'s named routes.

**Key Features & Changes:**

*   **Router Redirect Logic (`redirection.dart`):**
    *   A new file, `redirection.dart`, has been created as a part of `router.dart` (likely using a `part of` directive).
    *   This file implements the core redirect logic for `GoRouter`.
    *   **Onboarding Check:** It first checks if the user has completed the onboarding process (e.g., by checking a value in `SharedPreferences` via a Riverpod provider).
        *   If onboarding is not complete, and the user is not already on an onboarding-related screen, they are redirected to the onboarding screen.
    *   **Authentication Check:** If onboarding is complete, it then checks the user's authentication status (e.g., via an auth provider).
        *   If the user is not authenticated and is trying to access a protected route, they are redirected to a sign-in screen.
        *   If authenticated, or accessing public routes, navigation proceeds as requested (or to a default authenticated screen).
    *   This logic ensures users are guided to the appropriate starting point in the app based on their current state (`feat: create redirection.dart...`).
*   **Navigation Refactoring & Improvements:**
    *   Navigation calls in `sign_up_screen.dart`, `sign_in_screen.dart`, and `profile_screen.dart` have been updated from `Navigator.pushNamed` to `context.goNamed` (or `context.pushNamed` if appropriate within `go_router`'s context), aligning with the `go_router` methodology (`refactor: ...replace pushNamed by goNamed...`).
*   **Code Quality Enhancements:**
    *   A `//TODO` comment has been removed from `main.dart`, indicating a task completion or cleanup (`refactor: 1 - remove //TODO from main.dart...`).
    *   `if (context.mounted)` checks have been added in `onboard_screen.dart` and `app_button.dart` before using the `BuildContext` in asynchronous operations. This is a good practice to prevent errors if the widget is removed from the tree before the async operation completes (`refactor: ...2 - check if (context.mounted)...`).

**How to Test:**

1.  **Onboarding Redirect Logic:**
    *   **New User (Onboarding Not Seen):**
        *   Clear app data (or simulate a new user state where onboarding is not marked as completed).
        *   Launch the app and attempt to navigate to a protected route (e.g., `/home`) or the root `/`.
        *   **Verify:** The user is redirected to the onboarding screen.
        *   Navigate directly to `/sign-in` or `/sign-up`.
        *   **Verify:** Access to these specific routes is allowed even if onboarding is not complete (as per typical redirect logic which usually bypasses auth/onboarding checks for these explicit destinations).
    *   **User Has Seen Onboarding:**
        *   Complete the onboarding process (so it's marked as seen).
        *   Close and relaunch, or attempt to navigate to `/onboarding`.
        *   **Verify:** The user is *not* redirected to onboarding again and proceeds to the next check (authentication) or their intended destination if not `/onboarding`.
2.  **Authentication Redirect Logic (After Onboarding is Seen):**
    *   **Unauthenticated User:**
        *   Ensure onboarding is marked as complete.
        *   Ensure the user is logged out.
        *   Attempt to navigate to a protected route (e.g., `/profile`, `/workout-list`).
        *   **Verify:** The user is redirected to the sign-in screen (`/sign-in`).
    *   **Authenticated User:**
        *   Ensure onboarding is marked as complete.
        *   Log in as a user.
        *   Attempt to navigate to `/sign-in` or `/sign-up`.
        *   **Verify:** The user might be redirected away from sign-in/sign-up to a main app screen (common behavior, depends on your exact redirect rules if an authenticated user tries to access auth pages).
        *   Navigate to protected routes.
        *   **Verify:** Access is granted.
3.  **Navigation with `goNamed`:**
    *   Trigger navigation from `sign_up_screen.dart`, `sign_in_screen.dart`, and `profile_screen.dart`.
    *   **Verify:** Navigation works correctly using `goNamed` to the intended destinations.
4.  **`context.mounted` Checks:**
    *   For `onboard_screen.dart` and `app_button.dart`, if there are async operations followed by `context` usage:
        *   Try to trigger a scenario where the widget might be disposed before the async operation completes (e.g., quickly navigate away after initiating the action). This can be hard to reliably test manually but review the code to ensure the check is placed correctly.
        *   **Verify (Code Review):** The `if (context.mounted)` check correctly guards `BuildContext` usage after an `await`.
5.  **No Regressions:**
    *   Perform general app navigation and functionality checks to ensure no regressions were introduced.

**Context:**

This PR significantly improves the user flow by implementing intelligent routing redirects based on onboarding and authentication status, ensuring users always land on the appropriate screen. The accompanying refactorings enhance code robustness and maintain consistency with the `go_router` navigation paradigm. This is a crucial step for a polished user experience.

issue.title: Spanish nouns that switch their articles

type.name: Feature
type.description: A request, idea, or new functionality

issue.body:
### Terms

- [X] I have searched [open and closed feature requests](https://github.com/scribe-org/Scribe-Data/issues?q=is%3Aissue+label%3Afeature)
- [X] I agree to follow Scribe-Data's [Code of Conduct](https://github.com/scribe-org/Scribe-Data/blob/main/.github/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md)

### Description

This issue deals with adding data to [Wikidata](https://www.wikidata.org/) that could indicate which nouns in Spanish switch their articles to avoid difficult pronunciations. An example: agua (water) is feminine, but it's "el agua" to avoid "la agua" (but still "las aguas").

It would be convenient if [Wikidata](https://www.wikidata.org/) would also have a widely used article property such that nouns that have articles that don't match their gender could be indicated when they're annotated. This could be as simple as putting the correct article in the gender annotation.
